Paracelsus said that two men can argue, fight, debate, quarrel, go to war against each other, etc. but be in a secret spiritual friendship. Similar to how J. Evola remarked the Crusades consisted of Muslims and Europeans offering each other an opportunity for religious martyrdom.

I recall the Screwtape Letters also had a paragraph about two enemy soldiers dying to each other's hand and then immediately starting to laugh and embracing each other once they saw their dead bodies below and realized that they had died together. So I guess it's a running theme.
